Hi,

Kannan Varadhan &lt;kannan@oar.net&gt; writes:
&gt;  For some strange reason, our nameserver got busy the other day, trying
&gt;  to reverse resolve an address.  The address it was attempting to
&gt;  reverse resolve was/is 130.113.0.69.  When I tried repeating the
&gt;  phenomenon by querying one of the root name servers, I got back NS
&gt;  RR's for the reverse mapping, but no glue RRs in the additional
&gt;  section.

        That's us (McMaster.CA). We used to be just a lowly netnorth
site with only an MX wildcard pointer for the domain, but now we are
enlightened and can talk on the internet. When I put up our
authoritative DNS, I registered it with the NIC for the reverse
translations, and with John Demco (.CA registrar) for the forward
translation. The NIC put in the address without any glue records (I
thought that you had to???) and John sent me mail which didn't get
delivered for reasons that I don't understand. His followup note got
delivered, and I have replied, and we should be clear of this shortly.
blackadder is 130.113.0.62 if anyone cares, which they shouldn't ....

&gt;  Is this the right scheme of approaching things?  Or, am I missing
&gt;  something blatantly obvious, or obviously blatant here?  Here is a
&gt;  transcript of what I tried, using dig.

        Ummmm what is dig, and can I get one? It looks like the sort
of thing I'm gonna want around ....

-Fred Whiteside
 McMaster PostMaster, DNS flunky, and The Guy To Blame ...

